natural problem: Find the range of the function \[f(x) = \left\{ \begin{aligned} x^2 & \quad \text{ if } x \le 0 \\ x^3 - 5 & \quad \text{ if } x > 0. \end{aligned} \right.\]
natural solution: For $x \le 0,$ the expression $x^2$ takes all nonnegative values. Meanwhile, for $x > 0,$ the expression $x^3$ takes all positive values, so $x^3 - 5$ takes all values in the interval $(-5, \infty).$ It follows that the range of $f(x)$ is the union of the two intervals $[0, \infty)$ and $(-5, \infty).$ Because the second interval contains the first one, the range of $f(x)$ is simply $\boxed{(-5, \infty)}.$
